 A joint Moscow-Brussels approach would improve the chances of both increasing their relative strength vis-à-vis the USA, but serious cleavages threaten to undermine such a ‘greater European’ common view on security. Wagnsson considers the extent to which the major European players pursue similar objectives, and assesses the possible implications for and the chances of greater Europe emerging as a cohesive global actor. This meticulously researched book will interest scholars and students with an interest in international security, the EU’s international role, European international relations and Russian security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSecurity, InternationalzEurope. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh  a9/11.  aEU member states.  aEuropean Union.  aIraq.  aKosovo.  aRussia.  agreater Europe.  ainternational security.  aleadership elites.  apolicy statements.  aterrorist attacks.1 aWagnsson, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779237240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792372423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792372/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles